North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened their distrust of the United States and that under these circumstances the country would not unilaterally abandon its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s Annual General Assembly last year that North Korea “had taken essential action out of good will,” for example stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and committing itself not to multiply nuclear weapons and technologies.
“We don’t see a response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances we will never unilaterally arm ourselves first.”
While Ri reiterated North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant insofar as it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between an incumbent U.S. President and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim had pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for an official end to the Korean War from 1950 to 1953, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes calls for a easing of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on “first denuclearization” and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by coercion, and is even against the “explanation of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can force us to kneel is a concussion of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our distrust.”
Ri did not agree to plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party on the denuclearization issue instead of the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to this standstill.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’ speech differed enormously from his speech last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the mainland of the United States with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump described Kim as a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened the “total destruction” of North Korea last year, overthrew Kim at the United Nations with praise for his courage in terms of disarmament steps, but said that there is still a lot of work to be done and the sanctions should remain in force until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo, however, told the UN Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the Security Council’s sanctions must definitely continue vigorously until we have reached full, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry out Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the edge of the UN General Assembly and then said he will visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare a second summit.
