Harvard students learn in one course, enough to sleep
A new course at Harvard University will ensure that all undergraduate students get more sleep this year, which is a measure against the spreading macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unneeded when it comes to paying attention.
Designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, the course is, in his opinion, the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about it now, in my last year?’
According to her words, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
This year’s first course explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and managing director of the university’s health services, said the university had opted for the introduction of the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students will see the image of a room in a dormitory and click on coffee cups, curtains, training shoes and books, providing information on the effects of caffeine and light as well as on the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
They are then encouraged to think about their daily routine using a map of the university grounds with interactive symbols.
“We know it won’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of “shifting a night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-growing pressure on students made the lack of sleep a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and weight gain could also be avoided as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode, so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who is studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course, having completed one of his courses in Harvard last year.
He said the course opened his eyes to him and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar degree program before enrolling in their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler’s recommendation, students should set an alarm clock for sleep time and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” that emanates from electronic screens and LED lighting and can get the circadian rhythm out of the clock, leading to problems with falling asleep.
