Then a map and a report of the habitat are created to create a detailed picture of their behavior at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help determine the benefits of habitat management measures, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
The bat stocks in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to the loss of habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as well as flycatchers and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation to detect insects and obstacles in their trajectory.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the subject of bats very seriously.
