Why Beijing could benefit from the US-China trade war
The opening ointments of the trade war between the US and China were deafening. Although the battle is far from over, Beijing could benefit from a trench between the countries in the long run, my experts.
Donald Trump, the American president, fired the first warning shot at the beginning of the year when he fined important Chinese export goods, including solar cells, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week with new tariffs on $200 billion worth of goods, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China to the US.
Beijing struck back in the same way each time, recently raising punitive duties of five to ten percent on U.S. goods worth $60 billion.
China vowed to respond to any U.S. measure and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economic power will soon stumble.
Moving Washington to move in would mean giving up, but a public slump against the U.S. would be far too tasty for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, experts believe that if Beijing plays out its cards well, China could benefit from the long-term effects of the trade war by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision could create conditions for economic turbulence in either Washington or Beijing is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized,” says Abigail Grace, a research associate who focuses on Asia at the think tank Center for New American Security.
Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, the foreign minister said
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help in rebuilding the country devastated by the war lasting over seven years.
In a speech to the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure thanks to progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country, which they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government welcomed help in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept any conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
Europe won the Ryder Cup in Paris
Team Europa won the 2018 Ryder Cup and defeated Team USA with a 16.5 to 10.5 finish at Le Golf National near Paris.
The US has now lost six consecutive times on European soil and has not won a Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe won the crown back after Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points it needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had problems over much of the tournament, lowered his tee on the 16th track (par 3) in the water and lost to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari was able to shine in all his rounds and became one of 4 players who scored a 5-0-0 since the tournament began in its current format in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was beaten 5:4 by the player with the lowest ranking in Team Europe, Thorbjorn Olesen from Denmark.
The player with the world's best ranking, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 to 1 against Englishman Ian Poulter, who may have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spain’s Sergio Garcia, a veteran of eight Ryder Cups, became the best European Ryder Cup player of all time with 25.5 career points.
“I usually don’t cry, but I couldn’t hold back today.
It was a difficult year.
I am so grateful that Thomas chose me and believed in me.
I am so happy to win the trophy back.
It’s about the team and I’m happy to have made a contribution,” says the emotional Garcia after the European victory.
He passes the torch on to his compatriot John Rahm, who won against American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday 2:1 in the individual encounters.
I’m so incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, whom I’ve been following on TV since I was a kid,” said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four of his games in France and now has a Ryder Cup balance of 13-21-3.
A strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 important titles and is surpassed only by Jack Nicklaus.
Team USA had trouble finding the fairways throughout the weekend, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who posted top-class performances throughout the tournament.
American captain Jim Furyk said after a disappointing performance of his team: “I’m proud of the guys they fought.
There was a time this morning when we had put pressure on Europe.
We didn't do anything about it.
Hat off to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players performed well.
We will regroup, I will talk to the PGA America and our Ryder Cup Committee and we will look forward.
I love these 12 guys and I’m proud to be their captain.
You have to pull the hat.
We were defeated.”
Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, more complete flowering conditions are recorded, indicating decreasing concentrations.
A red algal flower extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas to the south of the Lee district.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Last week, average concentrations in or off the coast of the district of Pinellas were reported, low to high concentrations off the coast of the district of Manatee, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district of Charlotte, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of the district of Lee and low concentrations in the district of Collier.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In northwestern Florida, no new respiratory problems have been reported over the past week.
